  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>Ghoulbane</font> - Kullom Faithforge</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>Perhaps the stories of war were just rumor.

Perhaps, perhaps not.  I spent over week in Qeynos, with no sign of an invasion or a coup.  After speaking with the officers for the High Council, I was released from my post, and allowed to do some more adventuring to increase my skills and better ready myself in case the war does come.  So, I sent word to Ravenflight (who had long since left and returned to High Keep), and met him that night on the road to Qeynos Hills.  There was a farmer on the shore in North Karana that Ravenflight thought I should speak with.  Apparently, he had information regarding the Plague and perhaps some insight into the possible Bertoxxulous invasion.  We searched, but the farmer was no where to be found.  However, we did come across a man named Ryshon Hunsti standing near the water.  We spoke for a while, and he revealed that he had some information on a noble sword that he was willing to give to me if I was willing to take the quest.  I wholeheartedly accepted the quest, and he handed me a message for a dwarf named Kanthuk Ogrebane and said I could find him near Kaladim.  I thanked him, and Ravenflight and I went on our way to High Keep.

I never got a chance to hunt here, since last time I was on my way the High Keep is when I got the message regarding the war, and one of my guildmates, Tammytree Litefoot, gave us a teleport to North Karana.  This time, however, the trip was considerably less eventful, and we finally made it to High Keep itself.  Ravenflight took me through the halls of the mountain keep, and led me to the bank where he bound my spirit, just in case.  We wasted no time joining a group of adventurers in the mines, and thus began to hunt the goblins.

Ravenflight warned me that it was dangerous here, but I thought that I had been fighting goblins since I first set out on my adventures.  I didn't figure that these would really be that much different.  Well.  I honestly can say that I couldn't have been more wrong.  In my first fight, I realized how strong these goblins were.  They hit much harder and faster than their cousins in Butcherblock, and their spellcasters had power I had never seen before in their race.  I knew I could never take one of these alone... luckily, I never had to.  We worked together well, and our own injuries were light, even though we went through many goblins that day.  I learned more about combat that day than I had learned in a week of fighting crocs in Oasis.  Plus the whole place was a set of mines!  Where better for a dwarf to hone his skills?  On a side note, I heard that the Runnyeye goblins have overthrown their old leader, King Xorbb, and have aligned themselves with the Pickclaw goblins, which is what we fought now.  I've heard that evil will always turn in on itself, so this news doesn't surprise me in the least.

It was on one of these goblins that I found a small scroll, with the name "Amstaf" inscribed on it.  I thought it was curious, and I tucked it away in a bag at my side.  It's significance wouldn't come to me until later, after I had spent some time in the mines, increasing my skills.  You see, Ravenflight left to go help another friend of ours, Wenjii (who I have found myself becoming more fond of.  She's a lovely young gnomish enchanter from Steamfront... but that's another story).  I very much wanted to go with him, but he left before we were able to meet up... humans are always in such a hurry.  In any case, I decided to venture out on my own and turn in the note to Kanthuk.  So, I made my way to Freeport to catch the boat to Faydwer.  Funny thing, I met Ravenflight and Wenjii at the gates to the city, and although I was very glad to see them, I had already made up my mind to return the note, so I bid them farewell and headed for the docks.

The boat ride was largely uneventful, and I found Kanthuk standing right outside the walls of the docks.  I gave him Ryshon's note, and with a smile, he asked me to sit with him while he told me a story.  It was a tale of him and a friend of his, a man by the name of Amstaf Trunolis.  As he related the story, it became apparent to me that Amstaf was a paladin, not unlike myself.  Kanthuk's story told of Amstaf's noble deeds, which in all honesty, could have been as much fantasy as fact.  At the end, Kanthuk said that he wasn't what ever became of Amstaf, and asked me to take a pendant to a lady named Llara near Unrest.  I bid him farwell, and since Unrest was not far from where I was, I made my way there.

I entered Dagnor's Cauldron, amd began to search for Llara.  Once I found the entrance to the Estate of Unrest, I took a quick look around, but was unable to locate Llara.  I figured she must be inside the Estate itself, so I followed the tunnel there.</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=41875'>Return to Kullom's Journal</a></td></tr>
